# Cookie Attributes

Cookies can contain security attributes that help protect user sessions.

Example:

```http
Set-Cookie:

session=abc123;

Secure;

HttpOnly;

SameSite=Lax
```

---

# Secure Attribute

Example:

```http
Secure
```

Purpose:

The cookie is sent **only over HTTPS**.

Benefits:

- Prevents cookies from being transmitted over HTTP
- Reduces the risk of network interception

---

# HttpOnly Attribute

Example:

```http
HttpOnly
```

Purpose:

Prevents JavaScript from accessing the cookie.

Without HttpOnly:

```javascript
document.cookie
```

could expose session cookies.

Benefits:

- Helps protect against cookie theft through XSS attacks.

---

# SameSite Attribute

Purpose:

Controls when browsers send cookies during cross-site requests.

Available values:

```text
Strict

Lax

None
```

---

## SameSite=Strict

Cookies are only sent when navigating within the same website.

Highest level of protection.

---

## SameSite=Lax

Cookies are sent during most normal navigation.

Balances usability and security.

Most browsers use this as the default.

---

## SameSite=None

Cookies are sent with all requests, including cross-site requests.

Requires the **Secure** attribute.

Used when cross-site functionality is required.

---

# Session Expiration

Sessions should expire after a certain amount of time.

Example:

```text
Login

↓

30 Minutes

↓

Session Expires

↓

User Must Login Again
```

Expired sessions reduce the risk of unauthorized access if a session cookie is stolen.

---

# Session Hijacking

Session Hijacking occurs when an attacker steals a valid session ID and uses it to impersonate the victim.

Example:

Victim:

```http
Cookie:

session=abc123
```

Attacker steals the cookie.

Attacker sends:

```http
Cookie:

session=abc123
```

If the server accepts the session ID, the attacker gains access without knowing the password.

---

# Session Fixation

Session Fixation is an attack in which the attacker forces the victim to use a session ID chosen by the attacker.

If the application does not generate a new session ID after login, the attacker may later use the same session.

Secure applications always generate a **new Session ID after successful authentication.**

---

# Why Attackers Target Cookies

Attackers often try to steal session cookies because they can provide immediate access to an authenticated account.

Instead of stealing a password, an attacker may simply steal the Session ID.

This is why session cookies must be carefully protected.

---

# Common Security Risks

| Missing Attribute | Possible Risk |
|-------------------|---------------|
| Secure | Cookie can be transmitted over HTTP |
| HttpOnly | Cookie can be stolen using JavaScript during XSS |
| SameSite | Increased risk of CSRF attacks |
| Long Session Lifetime | Stolen session remains valid longer |

